      <H3><A=20
      =
href=3D"http://nfocentrale.net/orcmid/BlunderDome/clueless/2005/03/trost-=
templates-for-raising-open.asp#Friday, March 11, 2005"=20
      name=3D"Friday, March 11, 2005"><FONT color=3D#660000>Friday, =
March 11,=20
      2005</FONT></A></H3>
      <DIV class=3Dposts><A name=3D111060368778289975></A>
      <H2><FONT color=3D#000080><!-- 2004-08-31 --><A title=3D"external =
link"=20
      href=3D"http://orcmid.com/erudizione/MSC-DS/">TROST: Templates for =
Raising=20
      Open-System Trustworthiness </A></FONT></H2>
      <P>On February 1, my proposal for an M.Sc in IT project =
dissertation was=20
      accepted by my Dissertation Advisor and approved by the Academic=20
      Coordinator of the program.&nbsp; I more or less went autistic and =

      comatose at that point, although I had prepared a project plan and =
the=20
      clock began running in relentless one-day-per-day fashion.&nbsp; =
My=20
      deadline is July 28 and my plan envisions the dissertation being =
submitted=20
      on July 4 (and already slipping slightly in a replan I am =
conducting this=20
      weekend).&nbsp; There have been many little stumbles getting =
started, and=20
      that is something for <A=20
      href=3D"http://www.43things.com/people/progress/orcmid/2356">43 =
Things</A>=20
      at another time.<BR><BR>Today, I want more of the world to know =
what this=20
      is about.&nbsp; That's mostly because I have other items to post =
about=20
      related work and materials that I find in my explorations.&nbsp; =
It seems=20
      useful to establish the perspective that gives rise to my=20
      interest.<BR><BR><STRONG>Why TROST?</STRONG>&nbsp; Well, FROST was =
already=20
      taken and I was grasping at straws.&nbsp; Once I had an acronym =
that=20
      worked in a (puny?) punny way, I held onto it.&nbsp; I even =
adjusted the=20
      name of the project at one point.&nbsp; I was careful to preserve =
the=20
      acronym.<BR><BR><STRONG>Templates?</STRONG>&nbsp; "Frameworks,"=20
      "patterns," and "templates" all work.&nbsp; It is not about laws =
or=20
      theories although principles, practices, guidelines, and =
approaches figure=20
      in. I can go either way with "model" but I think I'll save that =
one from=20
      further over-use just now.<BR><BR><STRONG>Raising?</STRONG>&nbsp; =
Sure, as=20
      in improving, enhancing, enriching, increasing, expanding, and so=20
      on.&nbsp; I am looking at the achievement of trustworthiness as a =
process=20
      and a journey, not an absolute result.&nbsp; I do mean continuous=20
      improvement along with resilience in the face of=20
      setbacks.<BR><BR><STRONG>Open-System?</STRONG>&nbsp; I had =
originally said=20
      Open-Source here.&nbsp; It didn't take long to realize that there =
is=20
      nothing in my vision for TROST that is peculiarly about =
open-source=20
      development (not to be confused with open-source licensing).&nbsp; =
I chose=20
      open-system trustworthiness in homage to OSI, the <A=20
      href=3D"http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/OSI_model">Open Systems=20
      Interconnection</A> effort that had much to teach us about=20
      interoperability and integration as well as network =
interconnection.&nbsp;=20
      I mean open-system in this general way.&nbsp; My attention is on =
ways in=20
      which we can address the trustworthiness of components and their=20
      integrations in any open-systems=20
      setting.<BR><BR><STRONG>Trustworthiness?</STRONG>&nbsp; Well, that =
should=20
      be easy.&nbsp; We all know trustworthiness when we see it, =
right?&nbsp;=20
      Maybe not.&nbsp; Starting out, I am looking at trustworthiness in =
terms of=20
      human arrangements for mitigation of the risks of everyday and=20
      not-so-everyday life.&nbsp; There is, most of all, the risk of =
dealing=20
      with each other, especially at a distance.&nbsp; I foresee a =
mapping into=20
      trustworthiness projected onto artifacts.&nbsp; I am not willing, =
at this=20
      point, to take my eye off of the <A=20
      =
href=3D"http://orcmid.com/blog/2004/12/heart-of-trust.asp">ultimately =
human=20
      and social nature of trust and =
trustworthiness</A>.<BR><BR><STRONG>Enough=20
      blather, where's the code?</STRONG>&nbsp; Uh, yes, this is an =
Information=20
      Technology project and that usually means that something will be=20
      built.&nbsp; So, along with some templates and a fair amount of=20
      metatemplating too, there is a feasibility demonstration involving =

      honest-to-gosh delivered software.&nbsp; The sofware will be =
produced=20
      using <A=20
      =
href=3D"http://toolbar.search.msn.com/results.aspx?FORM=3DTOOLBR&amp;q=3D=
%22open-box+software%22+Neumann">open-box=20
      development of an open-source component</A>.&nbsp; This component =
will=20
      integrate into open-system middleware, <A=20
      href=3D"http://odma.info/">ODMA</A>, on the Microsoft Windows=20
      desktop.<BR><BR>Here's more based on the definition of TROST as a =
<A=20
      href=3D"http://sourceforge.net/projects/trost/">SourceForge=20
      project</A>:<SMALL>
      <DL>
        <DT><B><I>Project Aims:</I></B>
        <DD>
        <UL>
          <LI>To deliver a framework for development and maintenance of =
software=20
          with demonstrable trustworthiness
          <LI>To demonstrate feasibility of the framework by applying it =
to=20
          delivery of open-source software for integration on desktop =
PCs
          <LI>To have procedures and practices that end-users, system=20
          administrators, and integrators can apply to confirm the level =
of=20
          trustworthiness asserted for a =
program</LI></UL><BR>&nbsp;&nbsp;=20
        <DT><B><I>Project Sketch:</I></B>
        <DD>Computer end-users and IT organizations find they must trust =
in the=20
        software that they use, having few means to directly appraise =
the steps=20
        taken to assure the trustworthiness of software that is offered =
to=20
        them.&nbsp; Although trust is a factor in the adoption of any =
software=20
        components for use, commercial adopters also express concern =
about the=20
        authenticity, legality, and quality of software obtained from=20
        open-source distributions.&nbsp; It is troubling when there is =
no=20
        distinct commercial organization that bears producer's risks and =
stands=20
        behind the software.<BR>&nbsp;&nbsp; <BR>TROST consists of a =
framework=20
        and procedures that are useful for incorporating trustworthiness =

        assurance into the development and delivery of open-system =
software,=20
        demonstrating such assurance, and verifying the=20
        assurances.<BR>&nbsp;&nbsp; <BR>The goal is to enable adopters =
of a=20
        software product to confidently establish:
        <UL>
          <LI>Whether the software distribution is authentic, and what =
that=20
means
          <LI>Whether the software is certified to be derived from the=20
          "official" source code, and how that can be and has been =
independently=20
          verified
          <LI>Whether there are assessments of the security, =
reliability, and=20
          integrity of individual source code constituents, how =
authoritative=20
          those assessments are, and the availability of details for =
independent=20
          review
          <LI>Whether the covered subject-matter of the software license =
has=20
          been asserted to be free of conflicting intellectual-property=20
          restrictions by its producers/contributers
          <LI>Whether a security threat model is defined for the =
software that=20
          addresses reconciliation to an overall threat model for the=20
          application in which the software is to be used
          <LI>When modifications and even revocation of assessments come =
to=20
          light, and any remedies that are available for discovered =
deficiencies=20
          in the software</LI></UL><BR>I fancy having each installable =
component=20
        be linked with the latest certifications asserted for it, =
supporting=20
        trustworthiness as a dynamic.</DD></DL></SMALL><STRONG>TROSTing, =
did you=20
      say TROSTing?</STRONG>&nbsp; More and more, I do say that.&nbsp; =
It all=20
      started because TROST was not availabe as a domain name.&nbsp; =
After=20
      looking for alternatives, I settled on <A=20
      href=3D"http://trosting.org/">TROSTing</A> an an useful expression =
for the=20
      practice of raising the trustworthiness of open-system=20
      components.<BR><BR>I found another interesting domain name.&nbsp; =
It's for=20
      email:&nbsp; <B>trust@worthiness.org</B>&nbsp; Not an original=20
      device.&nbsp; I couldn't help myself.&nbsp; It's not working yet, =
so hold=20
      back on the spam for now, ok?<BR><BR><B>On to Literature =
Search</B>.&nbsp;=20
      Now I get to suffer the fear and doubt of every postgraduate=20
      student.&nbsp; It's all been done already, it's been shown as not =
worth=20
      doing already; and so on.&nbsp; Yes, I am interested in leads to =
existing=20
      work, proposed work, past work, and the wisdom of the ages.&nbsp; =
I=20
      am.&nbsp; So lay it on me.=20
